'milestone': None, 'comments': 2, 'created_at': '2022-04-19T03:59:56Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-20T15:40:14Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'There seem to be some left-over class names on this page from the "Microsoft.Azure.Search" namespace, especially in the "Load an index" section.  For example, the "Note" below the code sample references `IndexBatch.New`, and the paragraph below that talks about how to handle the `IndexBatchException`, and neither of those classes exist under the "Azure.Search.Documents" namespace.

I was particularly interested to see how to reproduce the functionality we lost from the old function `IndexBatchException.FindFailedActionsToRetry()`.  I'm trying to upgrade an application to use the new NuGet package, and I don't see any easy, native way to do that, so I adapted the function from [the old source](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/Microsoft.Azure.Search.Service_10.1.0/sdk/search/Microsoft.Azure.Search.Data/src/Customizations/IndexBatchException.cs) to the new model as best I could.  It seems a strange omission from the new SDK.

---

There's a short sample from the SDK that provides some context: https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/sdk/search/Azure.Search.Documents/samples/Sample05_IndexingDocuments.md#searchindexingbufferedsender

I agree that the current description is confusing.  The best docs I've found on this setting are here in the Management REST API: 

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/searchmanagement/2021-04-01-preview/services/create-or-update#encryptionwithcmk

It appears that these settings are used to enforce CMK on all objects in a search service. Disabled/Unspecified is the default, and it means you can create objects on the search service that don't use CMK. However, if you require CMK on every object (index, indexer, data source, skillset, synonym list), you can Enable this setting to gain discovery over whether any non-CMK-compliant objects exist in your search service.

CMK is always implemented on a per-object basis, and I believe the best practice is to CMK encrypt on an as-needed basis (because it slows down routine operations, like queries). But I suppose if CMK is a hard requirement everywhere, you would need this setting to figure out if there is an object on your search service that doesn't have it.  Without this setting, you would have to [manually check every object (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/search-security-get-encryption-keys) to see if it had CMK enabled, so I can see how it helps.

SharePoint document libraries via Azure Search preview API:-

SharePoint Library Columns are included as additionalColumns while creating datasource for SharePoint , also included when creating suggestor via index - Multiple fields are added as suggestor based on requirement like 'search suggestions should come from complete content of SharePoint libraries which has documents + additional columns as metadata'.
"container" : { "name" : "useQuery", "query" : "includeLibrariesInSite=[https://{domain}.sharepoint.com/sites/{sitename};additionalColumns=](https://%7Bdomain%7D.sharepoint.com/sites/%7Bsitename%7D;additionalColumns=)
Title,Description,Explanation,Techology"}

Index suggestor
"suggesters": [
{
"name": "sg",
"searchMode": "analyzingInfixMatching",
"sourceFields": [
"metadata_spo_item_name","Description","Explanation","Techology"
]
}

Search Suggest REST API Call returns all lines of content(SharePoint Library) from columns instead of just one word or equivalent suggestor paragraph.

Example: if we type 'te' it returns as below:

1. takes a search term while a user is typing and suggests search terms such as book titles and authors across the documents in the search index, returning a small list of matches.
2. The search suggester, sg, is defined in the schema file used during bulk upload.
3. Next Steps
4. Create a new Search resource with the Azure Cognitive Search extension for Visual Studio Code.

Not getting suggestor terms how its described here on MSDN- https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/tutorial-csharp-type-ahead-and-suggestions#add-highlighting-to-the-suggestions.

Any suggestions will be useful. Thank you.

'updated_at': '2022-03-25T18:13:02Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Cognitive Search (CS) indexer is unable to enrich documents calling Azure Function (AF) endpoint. The AF is setup with EasyAuth and AppRoles to enforce authentication and the indexer's system managed identity is given permissions to execute the AF endpoint (a parallel setup to ensure AppRoles are effective is setup and working fine). Upon execution the following error message is returned:
```
"statusCode": 400,
"name": "Enrichment.WebApiSkill.entity-enrichment-skill",
"errorMessage": "Could not execute skill because the Web Api request failed.",
"details": "Web Api response status: 'Unauthorized', Web Api response details: 'You do not have permission to view this directory or page.'",
"documentationLink": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2106475"
```

This page lists System-Managed Identity auth as supported scenario, but it is unclear if additional skill parameters  need to be added to what is already [defined in the documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/cognitive-search-create-custom-skill-example?source=docs). 

[An example](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/cognitive-search-create-custom-skill-example#modify-the-code-to-call-the-bing-entity-search-service) also misses to point out authorization aspect of calling an external API and assumes AuthorizationLevel.Function that necessitates a `?code=*****` to be passed in the URI of the skillset definition.

What is the setup necessary to authorize a request from a Indexer/CustomWebSkill to an EasyAuth fronted Azure Function API endpoint?

```
"statusCode": 400,

"documentationLink": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2106475"
```

This page lists System-Managed Identity auth as supported scenario, but it is unclear if additional skill parameters  need to be added to what is already [defined in the documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/cognitive-search-create-custom-skill-example?source=docs). 

[An example](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/cognitive-search-create-custom-skill-example#modify-the-code-to-call-the-bing-entity-search-service) also misses to point out authorization aspect of calling an external API and assumes AuthorizationLevel.Function that necessitates a `?code=*****` to be passed in the URI of the skillset definition.

What is the setup necessary to authorize a request from a Indexer/CustomWebSkill to an EasyAuth fronted Azure Function API endpoint?

The AF is setup with EasyAuth and AppRoles to enforce authentication and the indexer's system managed identity is given permissions to execute the AF endpoint (a parallel setup to ensure AppRoles are effective is setup and working fine). Upon execution the following error message is returned:
```
"statusCode": 400,
"name": "Enrichment.WebApiSkill.entity-enrichment-skill",
"errorMessage": "Could not execute skill because the Web Api request failed.",
"details": "Web Api response status: 'Unauthorized', Web Api response details: 'You do not have permission to view this directory or page.'",
"documentationLink": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2106475"
```

This page lists System-Managed Identity auth as supported scenario, but it is unclear if additional skill parameters  need to be added to what is already [defined in the documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/cognitive-search-create-custom-skill-example?source=docs). 

[An example](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/search/cognitive-search-create-custom-skill-example#modify-the-code-to-call-the-bing-entity-search-service) also misses to point out authorization aspect of calling an external API and assumes AuthorizationLevel.Function that necessitates a `?code=*****` to be passed in the URI of the skillset definition.

What is the setup necessary to authorize a request from a Indexer/CustomWebSkill to an EasyAuth fronted Azure Function API endpoint?

-`moreLikeThis=[key]` is a query parameter in the [Search Documents API](/rest/api/searchservice/search-documents) that finds documents similar to the document specified by the document key. When a search request is made with `moreLikeThis`, a query is generated with search terms extracted from the given document that describe that document best. The generated query is then used to make the search request. By default, the contents of all searchable fields are considered, minus any restricted fields that you specified using the `searchFields` parameter. The `moreLikeThis` parameter cannot be used with the search parameter, `search=[string]`.
+`moreLikeThis=[key]` is a query parameter in the [Search Documents API](/rest/api/searchservice/search-documents) that finds documents similar to the document specified by the document key. When a search request is made with `moreLikeThis`, a query is generated with search terms extracted from the given document that describe that document best. The generated query is then used to make the search request. The `moreLikeThis` parameter cannot be used with the search parameter, `search=[string]`.
 
 By default, the contents of all top-level searchable fields are considered. If you want to specify particular fields instead, you can use the `searchFields` parameter. 
 
-You cannot use `MoreLikeThis` on searchable sub-fields in a [complex type](search-howto-complex-data-types.md).
